    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## Step 2 — Converting Data Types with `astype()`\n",
    "\n",
    "### What is `astype()`?\n",
    "\n",
    "Sometimes the data type pandas assigned is not the one you need for your analysis.\n",
    "`astype()` lets you **convert a column from one type to another**.\n",
    "\n",
    "Example use case:\n",
    "- `points` is stored as `int64` but your model expects `float64`\n",
    "- A `0/1` column stored as `int64` should be `bool`\n",
    "\n",
    "⚠️ The conversion only makes sense if the values are compatible.\n",
    "Converting a text column to `int64` will throw an error."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "bb334455",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Convert points from int64 to float64\n",
    "reviews.points.astype('float64')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "cc445566",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**What just happened?**\n",
    "\n",
    "- `points` was originally stored as whole numbers (`int64`)\n",
    "- `astype('float64')` converted every value to a decimal\n",
    "- 87 → 87.0 — same value, different storage type\n",
    "- Original column is untouched — `astype()` returns a new Series"
=======
    "**What just happened?**\n",
    "\n",
    "- pandas split the dataset into groups — one per unique point value\n",
    "- For each group, it found the minimum price\n",
    "- Result: cheapest wine at every quality level"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ff112233",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Using `apply()` Inside a Group\n",
    "\n",
    "Each group is a **slice of the original DataFrame**.\n",
    "You can access it directly using `apply()` and run any custom logic on it."
   ]
