<<<<<<< HEAD
    "**`dtypes` + `astype()`**\n",
    "The first check after loading any new dataset. Wrong data types cause silent bugs in machine learning pipelines — a price column stored as `object` instead of `float64` will break every numeric operation downstream.\n",
    "\n",
    "**`isnull().sum()`**\n",
    "Standard step in every Exploratory Data Analysis. Tells you exactly which columns have missing data and how much — critical before any modelling or aggregation.\n",
    "\n",
    "**`fillna()`**\n",
    "Used in data cleaning pipelines before training ML models. Models cannot handle NaN values — filling them with the mean, median, or a placeholder is a standard preprocessing step.\n",
    "\n",
    "**`replace()`**\n",
    "Used when datasets contain sentinel values like `\"N/A\"`, `\"Unknown\"`, `\"Invalid\"` — or when category labels change over time and historical data needs updating.\n",
=======
    "**`groupby()`**\n",
    "Used constantly in business analytics — revenue by region, sales by product category, clicks by campaign. Any time you need per-group statistics, `groupby()` is the tool.\n",
    "\n",
    "**`agg()`**\n",
    "Used in reporting pipelines where multiple metrics are needed per group simultaneously. Avoids writing repetitive code and keeps transformations clean.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Multi-Index + `reset_index()`**\n",
    "Multi-indexes appear automatically in grouped outputs. In production code, `reset_index()` is almost always called immediately after to keep the DataFrame in a clean, flat structure that downstream tools can work with.\n",
    "\n",
    "**`sort_values()`**\n",
    "Used in leaderboards, rankings, top-N analyses, and any output meant for reporting or visualization. Always sort before presenting grouped results.\n",
>>>>>>> 80fd5065e7b824ecea8d3c6d4564e2ab7239624f
