<<<<<<< HEAD
    "- Every column has a `dtype` — always check it after loading a new dataset\n",
    "- String columns are stored as `object` — not `string`\n",
    "- Missing values are stored as `NaN` and are always `float64` dtype\n",
    "- `astype()` converts types but does not modify the original column\n",
    "- `fillna()` fills NaN values — `replace()` swaps any existing value\n",
    "- Neither `fillna()` nor `replace()` modifies original data — they return new copies\n",
    "- Always run `df.isnull().sum()` as part of your first look at any new dataset\n",
=======
    "- `groupby()` splits data into groups — then you apply any function to each group\n",
    "- `value_counts()` is just a shortcut to a `groupby()` + `count()` operation\n",
    "- `agg()` lets you run multiple functions simultaneously — cleaner and faster than chaining\n",
    "- Grouping on **multiple columns** creates a **multi-index** — use `reset_index()` to flatten it\n",
    "- `groupby()` returns data in **index order** — use `sort_values()` to get value order\n",
    "- `sort_values()` defaults to ascending — pass `ascending=False` for descending\n",
    "- You can sort by multiple columns — pandas resolves ties using the next column in the list\n",
